<dl id="s17016bb"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="us17" href="#s17016bb">Ithaca: </a><a href="../../FF/unbs/s17all.htm#s17016bb">sector 16(bb)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Stable C of G lowest position unstable &#x3003; highest &#x3003; neutral</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The equilibrium is said to be stable, unstable, or <mark>neutral</mark>, according as the body, when left to itself, returns to its original position, moves still farther from its original position, or remains at rest in its new position. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> In all cases, if a body is in <mark>stable equilibrium, the center of gravity is at the <i>lowest</i> position</mark> possible under the circumstances; if in <mark>unstable equilibrium, the center of gravity is at the <i>highest</i> possible position.</mark> <small> Wentworth and Hill, <a name="TBOP" href="/udra/udex.htm#TBOP"><cite title="source">A Text-Book of Physics</cite></a> (1904), 46</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
